{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608550"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16004"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16004"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.31,0.06,0.19,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72909"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8695"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16004"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58379"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4693"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8130"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20806"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72909"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn infant is born with occipital skull defects and incomplete closure of the vertebral arches. The head is severely bent backwards with the face looking upward. The neck appears to be absent.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following neural tube defects best describes these findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anencephaly","Craniorachischisis","Encephalocele","Iniencephaly","Spina bifida"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis description is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Einiencephaly\u003C/strong\u003E, a rare and typically lethal neural tube defect. The condition is characterised by three main features: fixed retroflexion of the head, occipital bone defects, and partial or total rachischisis of the cervical and thoracic spine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other conditions can be distinguished as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnencephaly\u003C/strong\u003E involves absence of the brain and calvarium above the orbits, but does not typically involve severe retroflexion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECraniorachischisis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by an open neural tube along the entire length of the neuraxis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEncephalocele\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a protrusion of brain tissue and meninges through a defect in the skull\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpina bifida\u003C/strong\u003E involves incomplete closure of vertebral arches without the characteristic head retroflexion seen in iniencephaly\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost neural tube defects can be prevented through adequate maternal folate supplementation before and during early pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Iniencephaly is a rare neural tube defect characterised by extreme retroflexion of the head, occipital bone defects, and variable rachischisis of the cervical and thoracic spine.","Neural tube defects occur due to incomplete closure of the neural tube during weeks 3-4 of embryonic development."],"references":["Chikkannaiah P, Srinivasamurthy V, Satish Prasad BS, Lalyanayak P, Shivaram DN. Iniencephaly: Radiological and pathological features of a series of three cases. J Neurosci Rural Pract. 2014 Oct;5(4):389-93. doi: 10.4103/0976-3147.139994. PMID: 25288843; PMCID: PMC4173238.","Kadri H, Dughly M, Shehadeh Agha M, Abouharb R, Mackieh R, Bakleh S, Kadri T. Surviving against the odds: exploring the clinical and radiological features of iniencephaly compatible with life. Illustrative case. J Neurosurg Case Lessons. 2024 Mar 11;7(11):CASE2414. doi: 10.3171/CASE2414. PMID: 38467043; PMCID: PMC10936937.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58379"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16004"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58379"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T13:26:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T15:31:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8695"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attribu